question:
Consider the function \[f(x) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
\frac{x}{21} & \text{ if }x \text{ is divisible by both 3 and 7}, \\
3x & \text{ if }x \text{ is a multiple of 7 alone}, \\
7x & \text{ if }x \text{ is a multiple of 3 alone}, \\
x+3 & \text{ if }x \text{ is neither a multiple of 3 nor 7}.
\end{array}
\right.\] Define $f^a(x)$ as applying the function $f$ on $x$ successively $a$ times (for instance, $f^2(x)=f(f(x))$). What is the minimum integer $a$ that is greater than 1, such that the condition $f(2)=f^a(2)$ holds true?

